body:
Drizzle's `json()` and `jsonb()` columns return `unknown` by default, unlike Prisma which lets you type JSON fields via `Json` in the schema. You must use the generic parameter or `.$type<T>()` to get type safety.

```typescript
// Drizzle — no type safety by default
const users = pgTable('users', {
  metadata: jsonb('metadata'), // type: unknown
});

// Fix: use .$type<T>()
const users = pgTable('users', {
  metadata: jsonb('metadata').$type<{ role: string; prefs: string[] }>(),
});
```

Prisma handles this at the schema level with `Json` type, but the trade-off is you can't narrow the shape without a separate Zod validation layer. Drizzle's approach is more explicit but requires you to remember to add the type annotation.

Drizzle's relational query API (`db.query.users.findMany({ with: { posts: true } })`) only works if you define relations using the `relations()` helper AND pass them to `drizzle()`. Without this, `db.query` is undefined or missing tables.

```typescript
// schema.ts
import { pgTable, text, integer } from 'drizzle-orm/pg-core';
import { relations } from 'drizzle-orm';

export const users = pgTable('users', {
  id: integer('id').primaryKey(),
  name: text('name'),
});

export const posts = pgTable('posts', {
  id: integer('id').primaryKey(),
  authorId: integer('author_id').references(() => users.id),
});

// THIS IS REQUIRED for db.query to work
export const usersRelations = relations(users, ({ many }) => ({
  posts: many(posts),
}));

export const postsRelations = relations(posts, ({ one }) => ({
  author: one(users, { fields: [posts.authorId], references: [users.id] }),
}));
```

```typescript
// db.ts — must pass schema with relations
import * as schema from './schema';
const db = drizzle(pool, { schema });

// Now this works:
const result = await db.query.users.findMany({ with: { posts: true } });
```

Prisma doesn't warn you about N+1 queries. If you loop over results and access a relation inside the loop, each access fires a separate query. Use `include` or `select` with nested relations to eager-load in a single query.

```typescript
// BAD: N+1 — one query per user for their posts
const users = await prisma.user.findMany();
for (const user of users) {
  const posts = await prisma.post.findMany({ where: { authorId: user.id } });
}

// GOOD: single query with include
const users = await prisma.user.findMany({
  include: { posts: true },
});

// GOOD: select only needed fields
const users = await prisma.user.findMany({
  select: {
    name: true,
    posts: { select: { title: true } },
  },
});
```

Enable query logging with `prisma.$on('query', console.log)` during development to catch N+1 patterns early. The Prisma query engine batches some queries automatically, but explicit includes are always safer.

Drizzle prepared statements are compiled once and cached. If you change your schema and regenerate, the prepared statement object holds a stale reference. You must recreate prepared statements after schema changes.

```typescript
// This is compiled once
const getUserById = db
  .select()
  .from(users)
  .where(eq(users.id, sql.placeholder('id')))
  .prepare('get_user_by_id');

// Usage
const user = await getUserById.execute({ id: 1 });

// After schema change, you need to recreate the prepared statement.
// If you store it in a module-level const, restart the server.
```

In serverless environments, this is less of an issue since each invocation creates a fresh module scope. But in long-running servers, consider a factory function that recreates prepared statements when needed.

Prisma's interactive transactions (`prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => { ... })`) have a default timeout of 5 seconds. Long-running operations silently fail with a timeout error.

```typescript
// Fails silently after 5s with: Transaction API error: Transaction already closed
const result = await prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => {
  await tx.user.updateMany({ ... });  // slow operation
  await tx.post.createMany({ ... });  // never runs if above exceeds 5s
});

// Fix: increase timeout and maxWait
const result = await prisma.$transaction(
  async (tx) => {
    await tx.user.updateMany({ ... });
    await tx.post.createMany({ ... });
  },
  {
    maxWait: 10000,  // max time to acquire a connection
    timeout: 30000,  // max time for the transaction
  }
);
```

The `maxWait` option controls how long Prisma waits to get a connection from the pool. The `timeout` option controls how long the transaction itself can run.

Unlike Prisma where you use `@@id([col1, col2])`, Drizzle requires a separate `primaryKey()` call in the table definition's third argument.

```typescript
import { pgTable, integer, text, primaryKey } from 'drizzle-orm/pg-core';

// Composite primary key in Drizzle
export const userRoles = pgTable('user_roles', {
  userId: integer('user_id').references(() => users.id),
  roleId: integer('role_id').references(() => roles.id),
  assignedAt: text('assigned_at'),
}, (table) => ({
  pk: primaryKey({ columns: [table.userId, table.roleId] }),
}));
```

Forgetting the third argument and trying to chain `.primaryKey()` on both columns creates two separate primary keys, which will throw a SQL error. The composite key must be declared as a table-level constraint.

Renaming a Prisma enum value isn't a simple rename — it's a drop-and-create. If you rename `ACTIVE` to `ENABLED`, `db push` will drop the old enum and existing rows with that value become invalid.

```prisma
// Before
enum Status {
  ACTIVE
  INACTIVE
}

// After — this is NOT a rename, it's a new value
enum Status {
  ENABLED
  INACTIVE
}
```

For safe enum renames, write a custom migration:

```sql
-- migration.sql
ALTER TYPE "Status" RENAME VALUE 'ACTIVE' TO 'ENABLED';
```

Create the migration with `prisma migrate dev --create-only --name rename_status_enum`, then edit the generated SQL file before applying it.

Using `timestamp('col')` in Drizzle creates a `TIMESTAMP WITHOUT TIME ZONE` column. If your app handles multiple timezones, you must use `timestamp('col', { withTimezone: true })` to get `TIMESTAMPTZ`.

```typescript
// BAD: loses timezone info
const events = pgTable('events', {
  createdAt: timestamp('created_at').defaultNow(),
});

// GOOD: preserves timezone
const events = pgTable('events', {
  createdAt: timestamp('created_at', { withTimezone: true }).defaultNow(),
});

// Also set mode for JS Date vs string
const events = pgTable('events', {
  createdAt: timestamp('created_at', {
    withTimezone: true,
    mode: 'date', // returns JS Date objects
  }).defaultNow(),
});
```

The default `mode: 'string'` returns ISO strings. Use `mode: 'date'` if you want native Date objects. This is a common source of subtle timezone bugs in production.

Each Prisma Client instance opens a connection pool (default 5 connections). In serverless (Lambda, Vercel Functions), each cold start creates a new pool, eventually exhausting database connections.

```typescript
// BAD: new client per request in serverless
export async function handler() {
  const prisma = new PrismaClient();
  const users = await prisma.user.findMany();
  // Connection pool never released
}

// GOOD: singleton pattern
import { PrismaClient } from '@prisma/client';

const globalForPrisma = globalThis as unknown as { prisma: PrismaClient };
export const prisma = globalForPrisma.prisma || new PrismaClient();
if (process.env.NODE_ENV !== 'production') globalForPrisma.prisma = prisma;
```

For true serverless, use Prisma Accelerate or PgBouncer as a connection pooler. Set `connection_limit=1` in the connection string for serverless:

```
DATABASE_URL="postgresql://user:pass@host/db?connection_limit=1"

Unlike Prisma's `findUnique` which returns `T | null`, Drizzle's `select()` always returns an array. You must destructure or index manually.

```typescript
// Drizzle always returns array
const result = await db.select().from(users).where(eq(users.id, 1));
// result is User[], not User | null
const user = result[0]; // could be undefined

// With relational queries, use findFirst
const user = await db.query.users.findFirst({
  where: eq(users.id, 1),
});
// Returns User | undefined

// Prisma returns scalar directly
const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { id: 1 } });
// Returns User | null
```

When migrating from Prisma to Drizzle, audit every `findUnique` call — the return type changes from `null` to `undefined`, which breaks strict null checks.

Using `prisma.$queryRaw` or `prisma.$executeRaw` bypasses Prisma's type system, middleware, and soft-delete filters. Results are typed as `any` unless you provide a type parameter.

```typescript
// No type safety, returns unknown[]
const users = await prisma.$queryRaw`SELECT * FROM users WHERE age > ${minAge}`;

// Add type annotation
type UserRow = { id: number; name: string; age: number };
const users = await prisma.$queryRaw<UserRow[]>`
  SELECT id, name, age FROM users WHERE age > ${minAge}
`;

// WARNING: middleware (like soft-delete) won't apply to raw queries
// If you have: prisma.$use(softDeleteMiddleware)
// This will return deleted rows:
const all = await prisma.$queryRaw`SELECT * FROM users`;
```

Always use tagged template literals (not string concatenation) with `$queryRaw` to prevent SQL injection. Prisma auto-parameterizes tagged templates.

Unlike `create`, `createMany` returns only a count by default, not the created records. This is a Postgres limitation Prisma inherits.

```typescript
// Returns { count: 3 }, NOT the records
const result = await prisma.user.createMany({
  data: [
    { name: 'Alice' },
    { name: 'Bob' },
    { name: 'Charlie' },
  ],
});
console.log(result); // { count: 3 }

// To get records back, use createManyAndReturn (Prisma 5.14+)
const users = await prisma.user.createManyAndReturn({
  data: [
    { name: 'Alice' },
    { name: 'Bob' },
  ],
});
console.log(users); // [{ id: 1, name: 'Alice' }, { id: 2, name: 'Bob' }]
```

If you're on an older Prisma version, the workaround is `$transaction` with individual `create` calls, or use `$queryRaw` with `INSERT ... RETURNING`.

Drizzle's upsert doesn't have an `upsert` method like Prisma. You use `insert().onConflictDoUpdate()` and must explicitly specify which columns to update.

```typescript
// Drizzle upsert
await db.insert(users)
  .values({ id: 1, name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' })
  .onConflictDoUpdate({
    target: users.id,
    set: { name: 'Alice', email: 'alice@example.com' },
  });

// Use sql`excluded` to reference the conflicting row's values
import { sql } from 'drizzle-orm';
await db.insert(users)
  .values({ id: 1, name: 'Alice', updatedAt: new Date() })
  .onConflictDoUpdate({
    target: users.id,
    set: {
      name: sql`excluded.name`,
      updatedAt: sql`excluded.updated_at`,
    },
  });
```

There's no automatic "update all provided fields" like Prisma's `upsert`. You must enumerate every field in the `set` clause. Missing fields keep their existing values.

Prisma middleware (`prisma.$use()`) is deprecated since Prisma 5.0. Use Client Extensions instead, which provide better type safety and composability.

```typescript
// OLD: middleware (deprecated)
prisma.$use(async (params, next) => {
  if (params.action === 'delete') {
    params.action = 'update';
    params.args.data = { deletedAt: new Date() };
  }
  return next(params);
});

// NEW: Client Extension
const prisma = new PrismaClient().$extends({
  query: {
    user: {
      async delete({ args, query }) {
        return query({ ...args, data: { deletedAt: new Date() } });
      },
      async findMany({ args, query }) {
        args.where = { ...args.where, deletedAt: null };
        return query(args);
      },
    },
  },
});
```

Client Extensions are type-safe, scoped per model, and composable. Multiple extensions can be chained with `$extends()`.

The `dialect` and connection settings in your Drizzle Kit config must match your actual database driver. Mismatches cause silent migration generation failures or wrong SQL syntax.

```typescript
// drizzle.config.ts
import { defineConfig } from 'drizzle-kit';

export default defineConfig({
  schema: './src/db/schema.ts',
  out: './drizzle',
  dialect: 'postgresql', // must match: 'postgresql' | 'mysql' | 'sqlite'
  dbCredentials: {
    url: process.env.DATABASE_URL!,
  },
});
```

If you use `pg` driver but set `dialect: 'mysql'`, Drizzle Kit generates MySQL syntax migrations that fail on Postgres. Also ensure the `schema` path points to the file that exports all your table definitions.

Prisma's `prisma db seed` command doesn't run TypeScript natively. You must configure the seed command in `package.json` with a TypeScript runner.

```json
// package.json
{
  "prisma": {
    "seed": "tsx prisma/seed.ts"
  }
}
```

```typescript
// prisma/seed.ts
import { PrismaClient } from '@prisma/client';
const prisma = new PrismaClient();

async function main() {
  await prisma.user.upsert({
    where: { email: 'admin@example.com' },
    update: {},
    create: { email: 'admin@example.com', name: 'Admin', role: 'ADMIN' },
  });
}

main()
  .catch(console.error)
  .finally(() => prisma.$disconnect());
```

Use `upsert` in seeds so they're idempotent — running the seed twice doesn't create duplicates. Run with `npx prisma db seed`.

Drizzle's `db.transaction()` behavior on error varies by driver. With `node-postgres`, thrown errors auto-rollback. With some HTTP-based drivers (Neon serverless, PlanetScale), you may need explicit rollback.

```typescript
// node-postgres: auto-rollback on throw
await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  await tx.insert(users).values({ name: 'Alice' });
  throw new Error('abort'); // auto-rollback
});

// Neon serverless HTTP: use try/catch with explicit rollback
await db.transaction(async (tx) => {
  try {
    await tx.insert(users).values({ name: 'Alice' });
    await tx.insert(posts).values({ title: 'Hello' });
  } catch (e) {
    tx.rollback();
    throw e;
  }
});
```

Always test transaction rollback behavior with your specific driver. The Drizzle docs are driver-specific on this topic.

You can't use `findUnique` with non-unique fields. Prisma enforces this at the type level — only fields marked with `@unique` or `@@unique` are valid `where` keys for `findUnique`.

```prisma
model User {
  id    Int    @id @default(autoincrement())
  email String @unique
  name  String
  orgId Int
  role  String
  @@unique([orgId, role])
}
```

```typescript
// Works: email is @unique
await prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { email: 'alice@test.com' } });

// Works: compound unique
await prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { orgId_role: { orgId: 1, role: 'admin' } } });

// Type error: name is not unique
await prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { name: 'Alice' } });
// Use findFirst instead for non-unique fields
await prisma.user.findFirst({ where: { name: 'Alice' } });
```

If you split your Drizzle schema across multiple files but only import some of them when creating the `drizzle()` instance, the missing tables won't appear in `db.query`. You must re-export everything from a single barrel file.

```typescript
// schema/users.ts
export const users = pgTable('users', { ... });
export const usersRelations = relations(users, ...);

// schema/posts.ts
export const posts = pgTable('posts', { ... });
export const postsRelations = relations(posts, ...);

// schema/index.ts — barrel file, must export everything
export * from './users';
export * from './posts';

// db.ts
import * as schema from './schema'; // imports barrel
const db = drizzle(pool, { schema });
// db.query.users ✓
// db.query.posts ✓
```

If you forget to add a new table to the barrel file, `db.query.newTable` will be undefined at runtime with no TypeScript error.

When you `include` an optional relation in Prisma, missing relations return `null`, not `undefined`. This matters for strict TypeScript checks and React rendering.

```typescript
const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({
  where: { id: 1 },
  include: { profile: true }, // profile is optional
});

// user.profile is Profile | null, NOT Profile | undefined
if (user.profile !== null) { // correct
  console.log(user.profile.bio);
}

// Common mistake: checking for undefined
if (user.profile !== undefined) { // wrong check, always true
  console.log(user.profile.bio); // could be null
}
```

This is consistent with JSON semantics (null is a value, undefined means absent), but trips people up when they expect the JavaScript convention of optional = undefined.

Drizzle's `$defaultFn()` generates default values in your JavaScript code before the INSERT, not in the database. If you insert rows via raw SQL or another client, the default won't apply.

```typescript
import { v4 as uuidv4 } from 'uuid';

const users = pgTable('users', {
  // Default runs in JS, not in Postgres
  id: text('id').$defaultFn(() => uuidv4()),
  // Default runs in Postgres
  createdAt: timestamp('created_at').defaultNow(),
});
```

Use `.default(sql`gen_random_uuid()`)` for database-level defaults. `$defaultFn` is useful when you need a library like `cuid2` or `nanoid` that doesn't have a Postgres equivalent, but understand the trade-off.

To use multiple Postgres schemas (e.g., `public` and `auth`) in a single Prisma schema, you must enable the `multiSchema` preview feature. Without it, Prisma assumes everything is in `public`.

```prisma
generator client {
  provider        = "prisma-client-js"
  previewFeatures = ["multiSchema"]
}

datasource db {
  provider = "postgresql"
  url      = env("DATABASE_URL")
  schemas  = ["public", "auth"]
}

model User {
  id    Int    @id @default(autoincrement())
  email String @unique
  @@schema("auth")
}

model Post {
  id    Int    @id @default(autoincrement())
  title String
  @@schema("public")
}
```

This is critical for Supabase users where auth tables live in the `auth` schema. Without `multiSchema`, introspection only sees the `public` schema.

Drizzle provides two type helpers that produce different types — `InferSelectModel` includes all columns (with defaults resolved), while `InferInsertModel` makes columns with defaults optional.

```typescript
import { InferSelectModel, InferInsertModel } from 'drizzle-orm';

const users = pgTable('users', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
  name: text('name').notNull(),
  role: text('role').default('user'),
  createdAt: timestamp('created_at').defaultNow(),
});

type User = InferSelectModel<typeof users>;
// { id: number; name: string; role: string | null; createdAt: Date | null }

type NewUser = InferInsertModel<typeof users>;
// { id?: number; name: string; role?: string | null; createdAt?: Date | null }
// id, role, createdAt are optional because they have defaults
```

Use `InferInsertModel` for API input validation types and `InferSelectModel` for response types. Confusing them leads to either requiring fields that have defaults or allowing undefined on fields that are always present.

MySQL's `DATETIME` type has second precision by default. Prisma's `DateTime` maps to `DATETIME(3)` in the migration, but if your MySQL table was created outside Prisma, you may lose millisecond precision.

```prisma
model Event {
  id        Int      @id
  createdAt DateTime @default(now())
  // Generates: DATETIME(3) in MySQL
  // But existing tables might have DATETIME (no fractional seconds)
}
```

If you're introspecting an existing MySQL database, check the column type. `DATETIME` truncates to seconds, so `2024-01-15T10:30:45.123Z` becomes `2024-01-15T10:30:45.000Z`. Use `ALTER TABLE events MODIFY created_at DATETIME(3)` to fix existing columns.

Postgres array columns in Drizzle need explicit type casting when inserting empty arrays, or Postgres can't infer the array element type.

```typescript
const posts = pgTable('posts', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
  tags: text('tags').array(),
});

// Works fine
await db.insert(posts).values({ tags: ['typescript', 'drizzle'] });

// May fail: Postgres can't infer type of empty array
await db.insert(posts).values({ tags: [] });

// Fix: use sql cast
import { sql } from 'drizzle-orm';
await db.insert(posts).values({ tags: sql`'{}'::text[]` });

// Or just use null for "no tags" if column is nullable
await db.insert(posts).values({ tags: null });
```

This is a Postgres behavior, not a Drizzle bug. The driver sends `[]` as a parameterized value and Postgres needs to know the element type to construct the array.

This error occurs when inserting or updating a record that violates a unique constraint. It's the most common Prisma error in production.

```typescript
// Error: Unique constraint failed on the fields: (`email`)
try {
  await prisma.user.create({ data: { email: 'taken@test.com', name: 'New User' } });
} catch (e) {
  if (e instanceof Prisma.PrismaClientKnownRequestError && e.code === 'P2002') {
    const field = (e.meta?.target as string[])?.[0];
    console.log(`Duplicate value on field: ${field}`);
    // Handle: show user-friendly error, or use upsert
  }
}

// Prevention: use upsert for idempotent operations
await prisma.user.upsert({
  where: { email: 'taken@test.com' },
  update: { name: 'Updated Name' },
  create: { email: 'taken@test.com', name: 'New User' },
});
```

Always catch P2002 in user-facing endpoints and return a 409 Conflict with a helpful message instead of a 500.

Prisma throws P2025 when `update`, `delete`, or `updateMany` finds no matching record. This is different from `findUnique` which just returns null.

```typescript
// Throws P2025 if user doesn't exist
try {
  await prisma.user.update({
    where: { id: 999 },
    data: { name: 'Updated' },
  });
} catch (e) {
  if (e instanceof Prisma.PrismaClientKnownRequestError && e.code === 'P2025') {
    // Record not found
    return res.status(404).json({ error: 'User not found' });
  }
}

// Safer pattern: check existence first, or use upsert
const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({ where: { id: 999 } });
if (!user) return res.status(404).json({ error: 'User not found' });
await prisma.user.update({ where: { id: 999 }, data: { name: 'Updated' } });
```

Note: `updateMany` does NOT throw P2025 — it returns `{ count: 0 }` if no records match. Only single-record operations throw.

P2003 fires when you reference a non-existent foreign key. Common when deleting a parent record that still has children, or inserting a child with an invalid parent ID.

```typescript
// Error: Foreign key constraint failed on the field: `authorId`
try {
  await prisma.post.create({
    data: { title: 'Hello', authorId: 999 }, // user 999 doesn't exist
  });
} catch (e) {
  if (e instanceof Prisma.PrismaClientKnownRequestError && e.code === 'P2003') {
    return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Referenced user does not exist' });
  }
}

// Fix: validate references, or use cascading deletes in schema
model Post {
  author   User @relation(fields: [authorId], references: [id], onDelete: Cascade)
  authorId Int
}
```

Set `onDelete: Cascade` for child records that should be deleted with the parent. Use `onDelete: SetNull` for optional references. Default is `onDelete: Restrict` which throws P2003.

When joining tables with identically-named columns (like `id` or `created_at`), Drizzle's select returns ambiguous results. The query may fail or return wrong data.

```typescript
// BAD: both tables have 'id' — ambiguous
const result = await db
  .select()
  .from(users)
  .leftJoin(posts, eq(users.id, posts.authorId));
// result[0].id — which id?

// GOOD: select specific columns with aliases
const result = await db
  .select({
    userId: users.id,
    userName: users.name,
    postId: posts.id,
    postTitle: posts.title,
  })
  .from(users)
  .leftJoin(posts, eq(users.id, posts.authorId));
// result[0].userId, result[0].postId — clear
```

Always use explicit column selection with aliases when doing joins. The `select()` with no arguments returns a nested object `{ users: {...}, posts: {...} }`, but explicit selection is more predictable and performant.

This Postgres error means your table hasn't been created in the database. Defining a table in your Drizzle schema doesn't create it — you must run migrations or push.

```bash
# Create tables from schema
npx drizzle-kit push
# Or generate and run migrations
npx drizzle-kit generate
npx drizzle-kit migrate
```

```typescript
// This defines the schema in TypeScript — NOT in the database
const users = pgTable('users', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
  name: text('name'),
});

// Error at runtime: relation "users" does not exist
const result = await db.select().from(users);
```

Also check: Are you connecting to the right database? Is the table in a different schema (e.g., `auth` instead of `public`)? Did you specify the schema in `drizzle.config.ts`?

This error occurs when you reference a table in a foreign key that hasn't been defined yet, or when there's a circular import between schema files.

```typescript
// BAD: posts imports users, users imports posts → circular
// schema/users.ts
import { posts } from './posts'; // circular!

// FIX: use relations() instead of inline references for circular deps
// schema/users.ts
export const users = pgTable('users', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
});

// schema/posts.ts
import { users } from './users';
export const posts = pgTable('posts', {
  authorId: integer('author_id').references(() => users.id), // lazy reference ✓
});
```

Drizzle's `.references(() => table.column)` uses a lazy callback specifically to handle declaration order. But circular imports in the module system itself can still cause undefined references. Put related tables in the same file, or use a barrel file.

Drizzle's `sql.placeholder()` only works with prepared statements, not with regular queries. Using it in a regular `db.select()` chain throws an error.

```typescript
// BAD: placeholder in non-prepared query
const result = await db
  .select()
  .from(users)
  .where(eq(users.id, sql.placeholder('id')));
// Error: Cannot use placeholder outside of prepared statement

// GOOD: use prepare()
const query = db
  .select()
  .from(users)
  .where(eq(users.id, sql.placeholder('id')))
  .prepare('get_user');
const result = await query.execute({ id: 1 });

// GOOD: pass value directly for non-prepared queries
const result = await db
  .select()
  .from(users)
  .where(eq(users.id, 1));
```

P2028 means your transaction timed out or you tried to use the transaction client after it completed. This is almost always a timeout issue.

```typescript
// BAD: async operation exceeds default 5s timeout
await prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => {
  const users = await tx.user.findMany(); // fast
  for (const user of users) {
    await tx.post.updateMany({ // slow loop
      where: { authorId: user.id },
      data: { status: 'ARCHIVED' },
    });
  }
}); // P2028 after 5 seconds

// FIX: increase timeout and batch operations
await prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => {
  await tx.post.updateMany({
    where: { author: { createdAt: { lt: cutoffDate } } },
    data: { status: 'ARCHIVED' },
  });
}, { timeout: 30000 });
```

Also fires if you store the `tx` reference and use it after the transaction callback returns. The `tx` client is only valid inside the callback.

If you call `.prepare('name')` with the same name twice (e.g., on hot reload in development), Postgres throws this error because prepared statement names are session-scoped.

```typescript
// BAD: re-registers on every hot reload
const getUser = db
  .select().from(users)
  .where(eq(users.id, sql.placeholder('id')))
  .prepare('get_user'); // fails on second hot reload

// FIX 1: Use unique names based on timestamp or random
const getUser = db
  .select().from(users)
  .where(eq(users.id, sql.placeholder('id')))
  .prepare(`get_user_${Date.now()}`);

// FIX 2: Deallocate first (raw SQL)
await db.execute(sql`DEALLOCATE ALL`);

// FIX 3: Use a singleton pattern similar to Prisma's
const globalForDrizzle = globalThis as any;
globalForDrizzle.__preparedStatements ??= {};
```

This only happens in development with hot module replacement. In production with cold starts, each connection gets fresh prepared statement namespace.

The connection pool is exhausted and new queries can't get a connection within the timeout. This happens under high concurrency or when queries hold connections too long.

```typescript
// Tune pool size based on your environment
const prisma = new PrismaClient({
  datasources: {
    db: {
      url: `${process.env.DATABASE_URL}?connection_limit=20&pool_timeout=10`,
    },
  },
});

// Or via connection string
// DATABASE_URL="postgresql://...?connection_limit=10&pool_timeout=20"
```

Connection pool formula: `connection_limit = (num_physical_cpus * 2) + 1`. For serverless, set `connection_limit=1` per function instance and use a pooler like PgBouncer. Monitor with `prisma.$on('query', ...)` to find slow queries hogging connections.

Drizzle's type system catches most mismatches at compile time, but some slip through — especially with `sql` template literals and custom types.

```typescript
const users = pgTable('users', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
  status: text('status').$type<'active' | 'inactive'>(),
});

// Type error at compile time (good)
db.select().from(users).where(eq(users.id, 'abc')); // number vs string

// Runtime error: operator does not exist: integer = text
db.select().from(users).where(sql`${users.id} = ${'abc'}`);
// sql`` bypasses type checking

// Fix: ensure correct types in raw SQL
db.select().from(users).where(sql`${users.id} = ${1}`);
```

Prefer Drizzle's typed operators (`eq`, `gt`, `like`, etc.) over `sql` templates. The type system is the whole point of using an ORM — raw SQL should be a last resort.

Deeply nested `include` statements or circular relation includes cause stack overflows. Prisma doesn't limit nesting depth.

```typescript
// BAD: deeply nested include can blow the stack
const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({
  where: { id: 1 },
  include: {
    posts: {
      include: {
        comments: {
          include: {
            author: {
              include: { posts: { include: { comments: true } } } // circular!
            }
          }
        }
      }
    }
  }
});

// FIX: limit nesting depth, use separate queries
const user = await prisma.user.findUnique({
  where: { id: 1 },
  include: { posts: { include: { comments: true } } },
});
const commentAuthors = await prisma.user.findMany({
  where: { comments: { some: { post: { authorId: 1 } } } },
});
```

As a rule, never nest includes more than 3 levels deep. For graph-like data, use separate queries or raw SQL with recursive CTEs.

In ESM projects (`"type": "module"` in package.json), Drizzle imports may fail depending on your TypeScript module resolution settings.

```json
// tsconfig.json — fix for ESM projects
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "module": "ESNext",
    "moduleResolution": "bundler", // or "NodeNext"
    "esModuleInterop": true
  }
}
```

If using `moduleResolution: "node"` (the old default), switch to `"bundler"` or `"NodeNext"`. Drizzle ORM ships with proper ESM/CJS dual package exports, but the older Node resolution algorithm can't find the ESM entry points.

Alternatively, if you can't change module resolution, import from the specific entry point: `import { pgTable } from 'drizzle-orm/pg-core/index.js'`.

P2014 means a required relation is violated. This often happens with nested creates when you forget to connect an existing related record.

```typescript
// Error: The change would violate required relation 'PostToCategory'
await prisma.post.create({
  data: {
    title: 'Hello',
    author: { connect: { id: 1 } },
    // Missing: category is required but not provided
  },
});

// Fix: include all required relations
await prisma.post.create({
  data: {
    title: 'Hello',
    author: { connect: { id: 1 } },
    category: { connect: { id: 5 } }, // or create: { name: 'Tech' }
  },
});
```

Check your schema for required relations (fields without `?`). Every required relation must be either `connect`ed to an existing record or `create`d inline.

This runtime Postgres error means you're inserting a record without a required field that has no default. Drizzle's type system should catch this, but it can slip through with partial inserts or spread operators.

```typescript
const users = pgTable('users', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
  name: text('name').notNull(),
  email: text('email').notNull(),
});

// Type error caught at compile time
await db.insert(users).values({ name: 'Alice' }); // missing email

// Sneaky runtime error: spreading partial data
const input = { name: 'Alice' }; // email missing
await db.insert(users).values(input as any); // bypasses type check

// Fix: validate input before insert
import { createInsertSchema } from 'drizzle-zod';
const insertUserSchema = createInsertSchema(users);
const validated = insertUserSchema.parse(input); // throws if email missing
await db.insert(users).values(validated);
```

Use `drizzle-zod` or `drizzle-valibot` to generate validation schemas from your table definitions. Never cast user input with `as any`.

When using `onConflictDoUpdate` or `onConflictDoNothing`, the `target` must be a column with a unique constraint or primary key. Postgres needs the constraint to identify conflicting rows.

```typescript
// BAD: 'name' has no unique constraint
await db.insert(users)
  .values({ name: 'Alice', email: 'a@test.com' })
  .onConflictDoUpdate({
    target: users.name, // Error! No unique constraint on name
    set: { email: 'a@test.com' },
  });

// GOOD: target a unique column
await db.insert(users)
  .values({ name: 'Alice', email: 'a@test.com' })
  .onConflictDoUpdate({
    target: users.email, // email has .unique()
    set: { name: 'Alice' },
  });

// GOOD: composite unique target
await db.insert(userRoles)
  .values({ userId: 1, roleId: 2 })
  .onConflictDoUpdate({
    target: [userRoles.userId, userRoles.roleId],
    set: { updatedAt: new Date() },
  });
```

Wrap Drizzle queries in a repository class for reusable, typed data access. This pattern keeps database logic out of your route handlers.

```typescript
import { eq, and, desc, sql } from 'drizzle-orm';
import { db } from './db';
import { users, posts } from './schema';
import { InferInsertModel } from 'drizzle-orm';

type NewUser = InferInsertModel<typeof users>;

export const userRepository = {
  async findById(id: number) {
    const [user] = await db.select().from(users).where(eq(users.id, id));
    return user ?? null;
  },

  async findByEmail(email: string) {
    return db.query.users.findFirst({
      where: eq(users.email, email),
      with: { posts: { limit: 10, orderBy: [desc(posts.createdAt)] } },
    });
  },

  async create(data: NewUser) {
    const [user] = await db.insert(users).values(data).returning();
    return user;
  },

  async updateLastLogin(id: number) {
    await db.update(users)
      .set({ lastLoginAt: sql`now()` })
      .where(eq(users.id, id));
  },

  async softDelete(id: number) {
    await db.update(users)
      .set({ deletedAt: sql`now()` })
      .where(and(eq(users.id, id), sql`${users.deletedAt} IS NULL`));
  },
};
```

This pattern works well with dependency injection in testing — you can mock the repository instead of mocking the database driver.

Implement soft delete globally using Prisma Client Extensions. This automatically filters deleted records and converts delete operations to updates.

```typescript
import { PrismaClient } from '@prisma/client';

const basePrisma = new PrismaClient();

export const prisma = basePrisma.$extends({
  query: {
    $allModels: {
      async findMany({ args, query }) {
        args.where = { ...args.where, deletedAt: null };
        return query(args);
      },
      async findFirst({ args, query }) {
        args.where = { ...args.where, deletedAt: null };
        return query(args);
      },
      async findUnique({ args, query }) {
        // Can't add where clause to findUnique, use findFirst
        return query(args);
      },
      async delete({ args }) {
        // Convert delete to soft delete
        return basePrisma[args.model].update({
          where: args.where,
          data: { deletedAt: new Date() },
        }) as any;
      },
    },
  },
});

// Usage — delete is now a soft delete
await prisma.user.delete({ where: { id: 1 } });
// Actually runs: UPDATE users SET deleted_at = NOW() WHERE id = 1

// Queries automatically exclude deleted records
const users = await prisma.user.findMany();
// WHERE deleted_at IS NULL
```

Add a `deletedAt DateTime?` field to every model that needs soft delete. Create a database index on `deletedAt` for query performance.

Implement both cursor-based (for infinite scroll) and offset-based (for page numbers) pagination with Drizzle.

```typescript
import { gt, desc, sql, and } from 'drizzle-orm';

// Cursor-based pagination (efficient for large datasets)
async function getCursorPage(cursor?: number, limit = 20) {
  const conditions = cursor ? gt(posts.id, cursor) : undefined;

  const items = await db.select()
    .from(posts)
    .where(conditions)
    .orderBy(posts.id)
    .limit(limit + 1); // fetch one extra to check hasMore

  const hasMore = items.length > limit;
  if (hasMore) items.pop();

  return {
    items,
    nextCursor: hasMore ? items[items.length - 1].id : null,
  };
}

// Offset-based pagination (for page numbers)
async function getOffsetPage(page: number, pageSize = 20) {
  const [items, [{ count }]] = await Promise.all([
    db.select().from(posts)
      .orderBy(desc(posts.createdAt))
      .limit(pageSize)
      .offset((page - 1) * pageSize),
    db.select({ count: sql<number>`count(*)` }).from(posts),
  ]);

  return {
    items,
    totalPages: Math.ceil(count / pageSize),
    currentPage: page,
  };
}
```

Cursor pagination is O(1) regardless of offset, while offset pagination degrades as page number increases. Use cursor for feeds and infinite scroll, offset for admin tables with page controls.

Use interactive transactions for operations that need atomicity with conditional logic. Use sequential transactions for simple bulk operations.

```typescript
// Interactive transaction: transfer funds with balance check
async function transferFunds(fromId: number, toId: number, amount: number) {
  return prisma.$transaction(async (tx) => {
    const sender = await tx.account.findUniqueOrThrow({
      where: { id: fromId },
    });

    if (sender.balance < amount) {
      throw new Error('Insufficient funds');
      // Transaction auto-rollbacks on throw
    }

    await tx.account.update({
      where: { id: fromId },
      data: { balance: { decrement: amount } },
    });

    await tx.account.update({
      where: { id: toId },
      data: { balance: { increment: amount } },
    });

    return tx.transfer.create({
      data: { fromId, toId, amount, status: 'COMPLETED' },
    });
  }, {
    isolationLevel: 'Serializable', // prevent race conditions
    timeout: 10000,
  });
}

// Sequential transaction: batch operations (no conditional logic)
const [deletedPosts, updatedUser] = await prisma.$transaction([
  prisma.post.deleteMany({ where: { authorId: 1 } }),
  prisma.user.update({ where: { id: 1 }, data: { status: 'DEACTIVATED' } }),
]);
```

Use `isolationLevel: 'Serializable'` for financial operations. Sequential transactions (`$transaction([...])`) are simpler and slightly faster than interactive ones.

Build dynamic WHERE clauses from API query parameters while maintaining full type safety.

```typescript
import { eq, like, and, gte, lte, SQL } from 'drizzle-orm';

interface UserFilters {
  name?: string;
  email?: string;
  role?: 'admin' | 'user';
  createdAfter?: Date;
  createdBefore?: Date;
}

async function searchUsers(filters: UserFilters) {
  const conditions: SQL[] = [];

  if (filters.name) {
    conditions.push(like(users.name, `%${filters.name}%`));
  }
  if (filters.email) {
    conditions.push(eq(users.email, filters.email));
  }
  if (filters.role) {
    conditions.push(eq(users.role, filters.role));
  }
  if (filters.createdAfter) {
    conditions.push(gte(users.createdAt, filters.createdAfter));
  }
  if (filters.createdBefore) {
    conditions.push(lte(users.createdAt, filters.createdBefore));
  }

  return db.select()
    .from(users)
    .where(conditions.length ? and(...conditions) : undefined)
    .orderBy(users.createdAt)
    .limit(50);
}
```

The `and()` function accepts `SQL[]` and combines them. If no conditions, passing `undefined` to `where()` skips the WHERE clause entirely. This is much cleaner than string concatenation.

Track who changed what and when using Prisma Client Extensions. This replaces the deprecated middleware approach.

```typescript
const prisma = new PrismaClient().$extends({
  query: {
    $allModels: {
      async create({ args, query, model }) {
        const result = await query(args);
        await logAudit(model, 'CREATE', null, result);
        return result;
      },
      async update({ args, query, model }) {
        const before = await (prisma as any)[model].findUnique({ where: args.where });
        const result = await query(args);
        await logAudit(model, 'UPDATE', before, result);
        return result;
      },
      async delete({ args, query, model }) {
        const before = await (prisma as any)[model].findUnique({ where: args.where });
        const result = await query(args);
        await logAudit(model, 'DELETE', before, null);
        return result;
      },
    },
  },
});

async function logAudit(model: string, action: string, before: any, after: any) {
  await prisma.auditLog.create({
    data: {
      model,
      action,
      before: before ? JSON.stringify(before) : null,
      after: after ? JSON.stringify(after) : null,
      timestamp: new Date(),
    },
  });
}
```

For high-throughput systems, batch audit logs or write them to a queue instead of inserting synchronously on every mutation.

Create a reusable seed script that can run multiple times without duplicating data.

```typescript
// seed.ts
import { db } from './db';
import { users, roles, userRoles } from './schema';
import { sql } from 'drizzle-orm';

async function seed() {
  console.log('Seeding database...');

  // Upsert roles
  const roleData = [
    { id: 1, name: 'admin', permissions: ['read', 'write', 'delete'] },
    { id: 2, name: 'editor', permissions: ['read', 'write'] },
    { id: 3, name: 'viewer', permissions: ['read'] },
  ];

  for (const role of roleData) {
    await db.insert(roles)
      .values(role)
      .onConflictDoUpdate({
        target: roles.id,
        set: { name: role.name, permissions: role.permissions },
      });
  }

  // Batch insert users with conflict handling
  const userData = Array.from({ length: 50 }, (_, i) => ({
    email: `user${i}@test.com`,
    name: `Test User ${i}`,
    roleId: (i % 3) + 1,
  }));

  await db.insert(users)
    .values(userData)
    .onConflictDoNothing({ target: users.email });

  console.log('Seeding complete');
}

seed().catch(console.error).then(() => process.exit(0));
```

Run with `npx tsx seed.ts`. Use `onConflictDoNothing` for data that shouldn't change, `onConflictDoUpdate` for data that should be refreshed on re-seed.

Properly manage Prisma connections in Express/Fastify servers with graceful shutdown and health checks.

```typescript
import { PrismaClient } from '@prisma/client';

const prisma = new PrismaClient({
  log: process.env.NODE_ENV === 'development'
    ? ['query', 'warn', 'error']
    : ['warn', 'error'],
});

// Health check endpoint
app.get('/health', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    await prisma.$queryRaw`SELECT 1`;
    res.json({ status: 'ok', db: 'connected' });
  } catch (e) {
    res.status(503).json({ status: 'error', db: 'disconnected' });
  }
});

// Graceful shutdown
process.on('SIGTERM', async () => {
  console.log('SIGTERM received, shutting down...');
  await prisma.$disconnect();
  process.exit(0);
});

process.on('SIGINT', async () => {
  await prisma.$disconnect();
  process.exit(0);
});

// Connect on startup
async function main() {
  await prisma.$connect();
  console.log('Database connected');
  app.listen(3000);
}

main().catch(async (e) => {
  console.error(e);
  await prisma.$disconnect();
  process.exit(1);
});
```

Always call `$disconnect()` on shutdown to release connections back to the pool. Without this, connections leak and your database hits its connection limit.

Implement multi-tenancy using Postgres schemas (one schema per tenant) with Drizzle.

```typescript
import { drizzle } from 'drizzle-orm/node-postgres';
import { sql } from 'drizzle-orm';
import { Pool } from 'pg';
import * as schema from './schema';

const pool = new Pool({ connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL });

// Create a tenant-scoped database instance
async function getTenantDb(tenantId: string) {
  const schemaName = `tenant_${tenantId}`;
  const db = drizzle(pool, { schema });

  // Set search_path for this connection
  await db.execute(sql`SET search_path TO ${sql.raw(schemaName)}, public`);
  return db;
}

// Middleware
app.use(async (req, res, next) => {
  const tenantId = req.headers['x-tenant-id'] as string;
  if (!tenantId) return res.status(400).json({ error: 'Tenant ID required' });
  req.db = await getTenantDb(tenantId);
  next();
});

// Provision new tenant
async function createTenant(tenantId: string) {
  const schemaName = `tenant_${tenantId}`;
  const db = drizzle(pool);
  await db.execute(sql`CREATE SCHEMA IF NOT EXISTS ${sql.raw(schemaName)}`);
  // Run migrations for the new schema
  await db.execute(sql`SET search_path TO ${sql.raw(schemaName)}`);
  // ... create tables
}
```

This approach gives complete data isolation between tenants. The downside is managing migrations across hundreds of schemas. For simpler multi-tenancy, use a `tenantId` column with row-level security.

Create type-safe update functions that only accept valid fields using Prisma's generated types.

```typescript
import { Prisma } from '@prisma/client';

// Extract update input type from Prisma
type UserUpdateInput = Prisma.UserUpdateInput;

// Create a typed update function
async function updateUser(id: number, data: UserUpdateInput) {
  return prisma.user.update({ where: { id }, data });
}

// Even better: restrict which fields can be updated
type UserProfileUpdate = Pick<Prisma.UserUpdateInput, 'name' | 'bio' | 'avatar'>;

async function updateProfile(id: number, data: UserProfileUpdate) {
  return prisma.user.update({ where: { id }, data });
}

// Usage — TypeScript catches invalid fields
await updateProfile(1, { name: 'Alice', bio: 'Hello' }); // OK
await updateProfile(1, { email: 'new@test.com' }); // Type error! email not in UserProfileUpdate
await updateProfile(1, { role: 'ADMIN' }); // Type error! can't escalate privileges
```

This pattern prevents accidental mass-assignment vulnerabilities where a user could update their own role or other sensitive fields by sending extra JSON fields.

Use `drizzle-zod` to auto-generate Zod schemas from your Drizzle table definitions. This keeps your validation in sync with your database schema.

```typescript
import { pgTable, serial, text, integer, timestamp } from 'drizzle-orm/pg-core';
import { createInsertSchema, createSelectSchema } from 'drizzle-zod';
import { z } from 'zod';

const users = pgTable('users', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
  name: text('name').notNull(),
  email: text('email').notNull(),
  age: integer('age'),
  createdAt: timestamp('created_at').defaultNow(),
});

// Auto-generated schemas
const insertUserSchema = createInsertSchema(users, {
  // Override with custom validations
  email: z.string().email('Invalid email'),
  age: z.number().min(13, 'Must be at least 13').optional(),
  name: z.string().min(1, 'Name required').max(100),
});

const selectUserSchema = createSelectSchema(users);

// Use in API routes
app.post('/users', async (req, res) => {
  const parsed = insertUserSchema.safeParse(req.body);
  if (!parsed.success) {
    return res.status(400).json({ errors: parsed.error.flatten() });
  }
  const user = await db.insert(users).values(parsed.data).returning();
  res.json(user[0]);
});
```

The generated schemas respect nullability and defaults. Columns with `.notNull()` become required, columns with `.default()` become optional in the insert schema.

Enable Postgres full-text search with Prisma using the `fullTextSearch` preview feature.

```prisma
generator client {
  provider        = "prisma-client-js"
  previewFeatures = ["fullTextSearch"]
}

model Article {
  id      Int    @id @default(autoincrement())
  title   String
  content String
}
```

```typescript
// Basic search
const results = await prisma.article.findMany({
  where: {
    content: { search: 'typescript & react' }, // AND
  },
  orderBy: {
    _relevance: {
      fields: ['title', 'content'],
      search: 'typescript react',
      sort: 'desc',
    },
  },
});

// Search with ranking
const results = await prisma.$queryRaw`
  SELECT id, title,
    ts_rank(to_tsvector('english', content), plainto_tsquery('english', ${query})) as rank
  FROM articles
  WHERE to_tsvector('english', content) @@ plainto_tsquery('english', ${query})
  ORDER BY rank DESC
  LIMIT 20
`;
```

Create a GIN index for performance: `CREATE INDEX articles_content_idx ON articles USING GIN (to_tsvector('english', content))`. For complex search, consider pg_trgm for fuzzy matching or move to a dedicated search engine.

Drizzle's `sql` template tag provides type-safe raw SQL while preventing SQL injection. Use it for complex queries that the query builder can't express.

```typescript
import { sql } from 'drizzle-orm';

// Type-safe parameterized query
const minAge = 18;
const role = 'admin';
const result = await db.execute(
  sql`SELECT * FROM users WHERE age >= ${minAge} AND role = ${role}`
);
// Parameters are automatically escaped

// Use sql.raw() for identifiers (table/column names) — NOT user input
const tableName = 'users';
const result = await db.execute(
  sql`SELECT * FROM ${sql.raw(tableName)} LIMIT 10`
);
// WARNING: sql.raw() does NO escaping — never use with user input

// Typed return with custom type
type UserStats = { role: string; count: number; avg_age: number };
const stats = await db.execute<UserStats>(
  sql`SELECT role, COUNT(*)::int as count, AVG(age)::int as avg_age
      FROM users GROUP BY role`
);
```

Always use interpolation (`${value}`) for values — they become parameterized queries. Only use `sql.raw()` for trusted, hardcoded identifiers.

Prevent lost updates in concurrent environments using a version field.

```prisma
model Product {
  id      Int    @id @default(autoincrement())
  name    String
  stock   Int
  version Int    @default(0)
}
```

```typescript
async function updateStock(productId: number, newStock: number, expectedVersion: number) {
  const result = await prisma.product.updateMany({
    where: {
      id: productId,
      version: expectedVersion, // only update if version matches
    },
    data: {
      stock: newStock,
      version: { increment: 1 },
    },
  });

  if (result.count === 0) {
    throw new Error('Conflict: product was modified by another request');
  }

  return prisma.product.findUnique({ where: { id: productId } });
}

// Usage in API
app.put('/products/:id/stock', async (req, res) => {
  try {
    const product = await updateStock(+req.params.id, req.body.stock, req.body.version);
    res.json(product);
  } catch (e) {
    if (e.message.includes('Conflict')) {
      return res.status(409).json({ error: 'Stale data, please refresh' });
    }
    throw e;
  }
});
```

The `updateMany` + version check is atomic. If two requests try to update the same product, only the first succeeds. The second gets a 409 and must refetch.

Configure Drizzle with Neon's serverless driver for minimal cold start latency in edge and serverless environments.

```typescript
import { neon } from '@neondatabase/serverless';
import { drizzle } from 'drizzle-orm/neon-http';
import * as schema from './schema';

// HTTP-based (best for serverless/edge)
const sql = neon(process.env.DATABASE_URL!);
export const db = drizzle(sql, { schema });

// For WebSocket (better for connection reuse in long-running)
import { Pool, neonConfig } from '@neondatabase/serverless';
import { drizzle } from 'drizzle-orm/neon-serverless';
import ws from 'ws';

neonConfig.webSocketConstructor = ws;
const pool = new Pool({ connectionString: process.env.DATABASE_URL });
export const db = drizzle(pool, { schema });
```

The HTTP driver is stateless — no connection pooling needed, each query is an independent HTTP request. Use it for Vercel Edge, Cloudflare Workers, and Lambda. The WebSocket driver is better for Node.js servers that make multiple queries per request.

Use Prisma's `$transaction` with an array of queries to batch multiple aggregation queries into a single round-trip.

```typescript
async function getDashboardStats(userId: number) {
  const [userCount, postCount, recentPosts, topAuthors, unreadNotifications] =
    await prisma.$transaction([
      prisma.user.count(),
      prisma.post.count({ where: { authorId: userId } }),
      prisma.post.findMany({
        where: { authorId: userId },
        orderBy: { createdAt: 'desc' },
        take: 5,
        select: { id: true, title: true, createdAt: true },
      }),
      prisma.user.findMany({
        orderBy: { posts: { _count: 'desc' } },
        take: 5,
        select: { id: true, name: true, _count: { select: { posts: true } } },
      }),
      prisma.notification.count({
        where: { userId, readAt: null },
      }),
    ]);

  return { userCount, postCount, recentPosts, topAuthors, unreadNotifications };
}
```

Sequential `$transaction([...])` batches all queries into a single transaction. Each query is typed independently, so you get full type safety on the destructured results. This is more efficient than `Promise.all` because Prisma can optimize the batch.

A production-ready Drizzle schema showcasing all common column types and constraints.

```typescript
import {
  pgTable, pgEnum, serial, text, integer, boolean,
  timestamp, jsonb, uniqueIndex, index, varchar, decimal,
} from 'drizzle-orm/pg-core';
import { relations, sql } from 'drizzle-orm';

export const roleEnum = pgEnum('role', ['admin', 'editor', 'viewer']);

export const users = pgTable('users', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
  email: varchar('email', { length: 255 }).notNull().unique(),
  name: varchar('name', { length: 100 }).notNull(),
  role: roleEnum('role').default('viewer').notNull(),
  metadata: jsonb('metadata').$type<{ theme: string; lang: string }>(),
  isActive: boolean('is_active').default(true).notNull(),
  createdAt: timestamp('created_at', { withTimezone: true }).defaultNow().notNull(),
  updatedAt: timestamp('updated_at', { withTimezone: true }).defaultNow().notNull(),
  deletedAt: timestamp('deleted_at', { withTimezone: true }),
}, (table) => ({
  emailIdx: uniqueIndex('users_email_idx').on(table.email),
  activeIdx: index('users_active_idx').on(table.isActive).where(sql`${table.deletedAt} IS NULL`),
}));

export const posts = pgTable('posts', {
  id: serial('id').primaryKey(),
  title: varchar('title', { length: 255 }).notNull(),
  slug: varchar('slug', { length: 255 }).notNull().unique(),
  content: text('content'),
  authorId: integer('author_id').notNull().references(() => users.id, { onDelete: 'cascade' }),
  viewCount: integer('view_count').default(0).notNull(),
  price: decimal('price', { precision: 10, scale: 2 }),
  publishedAt: timestamp('published_at', { withTimezone: true }),
  createdAt: timestamp('created_at', { withTimezone: true }).defaultNow().notNull(),
}, (table) => ({
  authorIdx: index('posts_author_idx').on(table.authorId),
  publishedIdx: index('posts_published_idx').on(table.publishedAt),
}));

export const usersRelations = relations(users, ({ many }) => ({
  posts: many(posts),
}));

export const postsRelations = relations(posts, ({ one }) => ({
  author: one(users, { fields: [posts.authorId], references: [users.id] }),
}));
```

